05798nam a22009855i 9780674061040DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2011    mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740610407 a10.4159/harvard.97806740610402doi  a(DE-B1597)178235  a(OCoLC)1013963976  a(OCoLC)1037979673  a(OCoLC)1041992873  a(OCoLC)1046613091  a(OCoLC)1047012253  a(OCoLC)1049658335  a(OCoLC)1054866187  a(OCoLC)840444606  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aDK68.7.A6bK35 2011 7aHIS0320002bisacsh04a958.104/51 aKalinovsky, Artemy, eauthor.10aLong Goodbye :bThe Soviet Withdrawal from Afghanistan /cArtemy Kalinovsky. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource :b11 halftones, 3 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00t Frontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Reluctant Intervention -- t2 The Turn toward Diplomacy -- t3 Gorbachev Confronts Afghanistan -- t4 The National Reconciliation Campaign -- t5 Engaging with the Americans -- t6 The Army Withdraws and the Politburo Debates -- t7 Soviet Policy Adrift -- tConclusion -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tA Note on Sources -- tBibliography -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe conflict in Afghanistan looms large in the collective consciousness of Americans. What has the United States achieved, and how will it withdraw without sacrificing those gains? The Soviet Union confronted these same questions in the 1980s, and Artemy Kalinovsky's history of the USSR's nine-year struggle to extricate itself from Afghanistan and bring its troops home provides a sobering perspective on exit options in the region.What makes Kalinovsky's intense account both timely and important is its focus not on motives for initiating the conflict but on the factors that prevented the Soviet leadership from ending a demoralizing war. Why did the USSR linger for so long, given that key elites recognized the blunder of the mission shortly after the initial deployment?Newly available archival material, supplemented by interviews with major actors, allows Kalinovsky to reconstruct the fierce debates among Soviet diplomats, KGB officials, the Red Army, and top Politburo figures. The fear that withdrawal would diminish the USSR's status as leader of the Third World is palpable in these disagreements, as are the competing interests of Afghan factions and the Soviet Union's superpower rival in the West. This book challenges many widely held views about the actual costs of the conflict to the Soviet leadership, and its findings illuminate the Cold War context of a military engagement that went very wrong, for much too long.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aDisengagement (Military science)vCase studies. 0aGeschichte Asiens. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2011z9783110261189oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PACKAGE ENGLISH LANGUAGES TITLES 2011z978311026123308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET PHILOSOPHIE UND GESCHICHTE 2011z9783110261257oZDB-23-DGE08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP Complete eBook Package 2011-2014z978311037488908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package 2011z978311037492608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045951708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066256640uhttps://doi.org/10.